OSI MODEL (7 layers)
The OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) model is a conceptual framework that standardizes how different network systems communicate.

OSI Model – Layers, Roles, Protocols
Application Layer
What it does: Interface for end-users and applications
Provides network services such as email, file transfer, browsing

Examples (Protocols):
HTTP / HTTPS
FTP, SFTP
SMTP, POP3, IMAP
DNS
Telnet, SSH
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Presentation Layer
What it does:
Data formatting, translate, encrypt/decrypt, compress
Turns data into readable form for Application layer

Examples:
SSL/TLS encryption
JPEG, GIF, PNG formats
ASCII, Unicode

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Session Layer
What it does:
Manages sessions between two systems
Handles authentication, session creation, maintenance, termination

Examples:
NetBIOS
RPC (Remote Procedure Call)
PPTP

------------------------------------------------------------------------
Transport Layer
What it does:
Ensures end-to-end communication
Reliability, segmentation, flow control, error control

Protocols:
TCP (reliable, connection-oriented)
UDP (unreliable, connectionless)
SCTP (used in telecommunication signaling)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Network Layer
What it does:
Routing, path selection
Logical addressing (IP addresses)
Packet forwarding

Protocols:
IP (IPv4 / IPv6)
ICMP (ping)
IGMP
Routing protocols: OSPF, BGP, EIGRP, RIP
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Data Link Layer
What it does:
Node-to-node communication
Frames, MAC addresses
Error detection (but not correction)

Protocols / Technologies:
Ethernet
Wi-Fi (802.11)
PPP
ARP (Address Resolution Protocol)
VLAN (802.1Q)

Sub-layers:
MAC (hardware addressing)
LLC (flow control)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Physical Layer

What it does:
Sends raw bits (0s and 1s) over the medium
Electrical signals, fiber optics, radio waves

Examples:
Ethernet cables (Cat5/Cat6)
Fiber optic
Hubs
Repeaters
Radio frequencies (Wi-Fi, Bluetooth)

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PART 2 — TCP/IP MODEL (4 layers)

The TCP/IP model is more practical and used in real networking.

Mapping OSI to TCP/IP
TCP/IP Layer	OSI Equivalent Layers
Application	Application + Presentation + Session
Transport	Transport
Internet	Network
Network Access	Data Link + Physical
TCP/IP Model – Layers, Roles, Protocols
Application Layer (Top)
What it does:
Same combined duties as OSI Layers 7, 6, 5
Provides services like email, file transfer, browsing
Protocols:

HTTP(S)
DNS
FTP, TFTP
SMTP, POP3, IMAP
DHCP
SNMP
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Transport Layer
What it does:
End-to-end communication
Data segmentation and reassembly
Protocols:
TCP
UDP
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2️Internet Layer
What it does:
Logical addressing
Routing packets across multiple networks

Protocols:
IP (IPv4 / IPv6)
ICMP
IGMP
Routing protocols (OSPF / BGP / RIP)
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Network Access Layer

What it does:
Responsible for physically sending frames
Hardware addressing (MAC addresses)
Protocols / Technologies:
Ethernet
Wi-Fi
ARP
PPP
ATM
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PART 3 — How Data Flows (Encapsulation/Decapsulation)
Sender side (Top → Bottom)

Application data
→ Transport adds TCP/UDP header
→ Internet adds IP header
→ Network Access adds MAC + physical signaling
→ Sent over wire/wireless

Receiver side (Bottom → Top)

Physical bits
→ Data Link extracts the frame
→ Internet extracts IP packet
→ Transport extracts TCP/UDP segment
→ Application layer reads final data
